# Curated by Haotian Du

**Protein design Agentic system**

**Tool catalog**

**1\. Design**

First tier: can start let users try playing with design tasks once these are ready

**RFdiffusion**, [https://github.com/RosettaCommons/RFdiffusion](https://github.com/RosettaCommons/RFdiffusion) (foundation model for backbone generation, unconditional generation, motif scaffolding, binder design, etc)  
**ProteinMPNN**,[https://github.com/dauparas/ProteinMPNN](https://github.com/dauparas/ProteinMPNN) (sequence design)  
**Bindcraft**, [https://github.com/martinpacesa/BindCraft](https://github.com/martinpacesa/BindCraft) (protein binder design, bindcraft have structure prediction \+ evaluation as part of the algorithm, basically only exit a design loop after metrics are met, but it would need pyrosetta license to run)  
**RFAntibody**, [https://github.com/RosettaCommons/RFantibody](https://github.com/RosettaCommons/RFantibody) (antibody design)  
**BoltzGen**, [https://github.com/HannesStark/boltzgen](https://github.com/HannesStark/boltzgen) (binder design, minibinder, antibody, cyclic peptide, good to support all formats, it has structure prediction as evaluation as part of the algorithm too)

Second tier: nice to have, would give users more flexibility, more choice to play with different model/tools  
   
**Chroma**, [https://github.com/chroma-core/chroma](https://github.com/chroma-core/chroma) sequence \+ structure co-design foundation model  
**Germinal,** [https://github.com/SantiagoMille/germinal](https://github.com/SantiagoMille/germinal) hallucination-based antibody sequence+structure design, the IgLM licensing is very tricky, need to work around that part  
**Caliby:** [https://github.com/ProteinDesignLab/caliby](https://github.com/ProteinDesignLab/caliby) Potts model-based protein sequence design method that can condition on structural ensembles  
**MASIF:** [https://github.com/LPDI-EPFL/masif](https://github.com/LPDI-EPFL/masif) Epitope prediction   
**ThermoMPNN:** [https://github.com/Kuhlman-Lab/ThermoMPNN](https://github.com/Kuhlman-Lab/ThermoMPNN) Thermostable protein sequence design   
**LigandMPNN:** [https://github.com/dauparas/LigandMPNN](https://github.com/dauparas/LigandMPNN) Designing protein for small molecule interaction

**2\. Scoring and evaluation**

**Structure predictions:**

First tier: most commonly used  
**AlphaFold2, ESMFold**, can leverage ColabFold implementation: [https://github.com/sokrypton/ColabFold](https://github.com/sokrypton/ColabFold)  
**Boltz-2:** [https://github.com/jwohlwend/boltz](https://github.com/jwohlwend/boltz)  
**Chai-1:** [https://github.com/chaidiscovery/chai-lab](https://github.com/chaidiscovery/chai-lab)

Second tier: nice to have as alternatives or let user able to call them  
**RosettaFold-AllAtom:** [https://github.com/baker-laboratory/RoseTTAFold-All-Atom](https://github.com/baker-laboratory/RoseTTAFold-All-Atom)  
**RosettaFold2:** [https://github.com/uw-ipd/RoseTTAFold2](https://github.com/uw-ipd/RoseTTAFold2)  
**Abodybuilder3**(antibody APO state prediction, metrics is pLDDT only): [https://github.com/Exscientia/abodybuilder3](https://github.com/Exscientia/abodybuilder3)  
**OmegaFold:** [https://github.com/HeliXonProtein/OmegaFold](https://github.com/HeliXonProtein/OmegaFold) (good for VHH prediction)

Key evaluation metrics

* Monomers: pLDDT, pTM, RMSD (vs design or native)  
* Complex-specific:  
  * iPTM, iPAE  
  * complex RMSD, target-aligned binder RMSD, binder-aligned RMSD  
  * iPSAE (Dunbrack lab): [https://github.com/DunbrackLab/IPSAE](https://github.com/DunbrackLab/IPSAE)

**Structure search, novelty report**  
**Foldseek** [https://github.com/steineggerlab/foldseek](https://github.com/steineggerlab/foldseek)

**Inverse folding, per-residue log-likelihood (for mutation effect evaluation, etc)**  
**ProteinMPNN:** [https://github.com/dauparas/ProteinMPNN](https://github.com/dauparas/ProteinMPNN)  
**ESM-IF:** [https://github.com/evolutionaryscale/esm](https://github.com/evolutionaryscale/esm) 

**Immunogenicity:**  
**NetMHCpan:** [https://github.com/tzina97/netMHCpan](https://github.com/tzina97/netMHCpan)

**Physics based structure evaluation:**  
**Rosetta/Pyrosetta:**   
Relaxation would be needed before evaluation because design model/prediction models are *not* energy-minimized  
metrics to report include ddG (binding energy), dSASA(interface area), sc\_value (shape complementary), hbonds (hydrogen bond), buns (buried unsatisfied hbonds)  
**OpenMM:** nice to haveâ€¦ more complicated MD-based evaluation  
**Propka:** [https://github.com/jensengroup/propka](https://github.com/jensengroup/propka) Predict pKa of ionizable residues on the protein

**Difficult scientific eval benchmark tasks:**

**1\. pH sensitive binder design**  
**Paper source: [https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/2025.09.29.678932v1](https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/2025.09.29.678932v1)**  
Example user query: Design a binder for Target X that binds at pH 7.4 but loses binding at pH 5.5â€“6.0.

Strategies:  
Strategy A: Interface Destabilization  
Goal: weaken binder-target interaction at lower pH  
Workflow: RFdiffusion generating backbone \-\> ProteinMPNN with histidine bias design sequence \-\> Structure prediction for good refolding/binding scores \-\> RosettaFastRelax-\> filter based on Rosetta ddG\_elec \>=0 (pH \= 0 vs pH \== 7\) & at least one histidine accepting a h-bond from a positively charged residue 

Strategy B: Monomer Destabilization  
Goal: destabilize binder fold only at low pH  
Workflow: Use RFdiffusion \+ proteinMPNN \+ structure pred or other binder design algorithms to come up with initial good binders \-\> Use Pyrosetta HBNet to buried His networks (Hisâ€“His / Hisâ€“Arg / Hisâ€“Lys) within the core \-\> optionally install the third back-up histidine \-\> filter for primary histidine hbond energy \< \-0.5kcal \-\> use ProteinMPNN to redesign environmental residues \-\> structure prediction and filtering

**Task Taxonomy rubrics:**   
Evaluates whether the agent *correctly classifies the task* and selects the right design strategy.

What is being assessed:  
1\. Did the agent recognize this task class: Conditional Binder Design?  
2\. Did it distinguish Strategy A vs Strategy B appropriately?   
3\. Did it infer the correct *design objective* (affinity maintained at pH 7.4, reduced at low pH)?

**Scoring levels**

| Score | Criteria |
| :---- | :---- |
| 0-Incorrect | Treats as generic binder design; no pH-responsive goal identified |
| 1-Partial | Recognizes pH requirement but selects wrong strategy (e.g., uses core destabilization when interface modification is intended or good interface pattern exist) |
| 2-Correct | Correctly maps task to Strategy A *or* Strategy B based on query |
| 3-Optimal  | Explicitly reasons about strategy selection (e.g., target has no positive residues â†’ Strategy A not suitable â†’ select Strategy B)  |

**Oracle rubrics:**  
What the oracle represents:

1. Constraint oracle: rules the agent must satisfy  
2. Scoring oracle: quantitative metrics determining success

Strategy-specific oracle definition  
Strategy A \- interface destabilization  
Constraint Oracle: 

1. Must introduce interface His near positively charged target residues  
2. Must not globally destabilize binder

Scoring Oracle: 

1. Rosetta ddG\_elec \>= 0  
2. \>=1 His accepting H-bond from Lys/Arg/His

Strategy B \- Monomer destabilization  
Constraint Oracle:

1. His network must be buried, not solvent-exposed  
2. Optional third backup His acceptable

Scoring Oracle:

1. Primary His Hbond energy \< \-0.5kcal/mol  
2. No structural collapse at pH 7.4 (AF2 pLDDT preserved)

**Scoring levels**

| Score | Definition | Criteria | Example indicators |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| 0-Violated | Breaks core mechanistic constraints or applies the *wrong* oracle for the strategy | â€¢ Misplaces histidines (e.g., surface His for Strategy B) â€¢ Strengthens binding at low pH (Strategy A failure) â€¢ No buried network for Strategy B â€¢ Causes neutral-pH misfolding | Strategy A: Î”Î”G\_elec \< 0; His not near Lys/Arg Strategy B: His exposed (SASA high), no HBNet network, AF2 collapse |
| 1-Pass | Meets minimum threshold requirements without optimization | â€¢ Executes required constraints exactly as specified â€¢ Single His correctly placed (A) or buried network formed (B) â€¢ Neutral-pH folding preserved â€¢ No reasoning beyond compliance | Strategy A: â‰¥1 interface His near positive residue; Î”Î”G\_elec â‰¥ 0 Strategy B: primary HBNet H-bond energy \< â€“0.5 kcal/mol; binder remains folded |
| 2-Strong | Satisfies constraints and actively optimizes multiple oracle-relevant factors | â€¢ Improves geometry, pKa environment, or redundancy â€¢ Balances destabilization vs folding â€¢ Re-designs environment (e.g., via ProteinMPNN) to strengthen network or electrostatics | Strategy A: modest positive Î”Î”G\_elec (\>0) with maintained packing and partial solvent exposure to preserve protonation; no excessive charge clustering Strategy B: buried Hisâ€“His or Hisâ€“Arg network with low SASA, primary HBNet H-bond \< â€“0.5 kcal/mol, and AF2 prediction retains high pLDDT and compact core packing |
| 3-Expert | Demonstrates deep mechanistic understanding, rejects invalid strategies, and adapts constraints based on environment \+ use-case | â€¢ Anticipates failure modes like: â€œthis His cluster is so tightly packed that it will likely depress His pKa and *remove* protonation at pH 5.5â€“6.0.â€ â€¢ Integrates UniProt/PDB, charge maps, SASA, and optionally pKa tools (PROPKA, MCCE, etc.). â€¢ Treats Î”Î”G\_elec as a window to tune into, not a monotonic â€œbigger is betterâ€ metric. â€¢ Bonus: performs pKa-aware reasoning, such as: â€“ evaluates local microenvironment to estimate His pKa shifts â€“ selects burial depth based on predicted protonation state â€“ positions His where protonation will *meaningfully* change energetic landscape | Strategy A: modest positive Î”Î”G\_elec (\>0) with maintained packing and partial solvent exposure to preserve protonation; no excessive charge clustering Strategy B: buried Hisâ€“His or Hisâ€“Arg network with low SASA, primary HBNet H-bond \< â€“0.5 kcal/mol, and AF2 prediction retains high pLDDT and compact core packing |

**Workflow automation rubrics:**

What is being assessed:  
whether the agent can execute the entire design-to-filter pipeline automatically, and how effectively it adapts to intermediate outcomes once the correct strategy is determined.

**Scoring levels**

| Score | Definition |
| :---- | :---- |
| 0-Not Automated | No steps are executed; workflow is only described conceptually |
| 1-Partially Automated | Some steps are automated, but the pipeline is incomplete and requires manual hand-offs |
| 2-Fully Automated (Linear) | Once a proper strategy is selected, the full pipeline runs end-to-end in a fixed sequence with automatic hand-offs, all required steps executed end-to-end |
| 3-Fully Automated (Adaptive) | End-to-end automation with simple condition-based adjustments, for example adaptive behavior and appropriate design-scale control.   |
